>
  <article class="en-lesson">
    <p class="en-lesson__crumbs">
      <a href="/en/">Hiraku</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">›</span>
      <a href="/en/lessons">Lessons</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">›</span>
      <span>Hōjōki</span>
    </p>

    <header class="en-lesson__header">
      <h1>Hōjōki <small>(The Ten-Foot Square Hut, opening)</small></h1>
      <p class="en-lesson__byline">
        Kamo no Chōmei (鴨長明) · 1155–1216 · written 1212 in the hills of Hino
      </p>
      <p class="en-lesson__japanese-link" lang="ja">
        日本語版: <a href="/library/kotoko1/hojoki-bouto">方丈記・冒頭</a>
      </p>
    </header>

    <section>
      <h2>Original Japanese</h2>
      <blockquote class="song" lang="ja">
        <p>
          ゆく河の流れは絶えずして、しかも、もとの水にあらず。<br />
          よどみに浮かぶうたかたは、かつ消え、かつ結びて、久しくとどまりたるためしなし。<br />
          世の中にある人と栖と、またかくのごとし。
        </p>
      </blockquote>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>English translation</h2>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          The current of the flowing river does not cease, and yet the water
          is not the original water.<br />
          In stagnant pools, the floating foam now vanishes, now coalesces,
          never lingering long.<br />
          People and their dwellings in this world are just the same.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p class="en-lesson__translator-note">
        Translation: project_procopios contributors (CC BY 4.0). For full
        translations, see Anthony H. Chambers, Donald Keene, or Yasuhiko
        Moriguchi &amp; David Jenkins.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Context: 1212 and impermanence</h2>
      <p>
        Kamo no Chōmei wrote <em>Hōjōki</em> in 1212, in a tiny ten-foot-square
        hut (<em>hōjō</em>) on the hillside of Hino, southeast of Kyoto. He was
        a former court poet who had been passed over for a clerical appointment
        and had withdrawn from official life.
      </p>
      <p>
        The book is, in its short span, an early Japanese example of the
        literary essay. After the famous opening, Chōmei describes the
        catastrophes that had struck Kyoto in his lifetime: the great fire
        of 1177, the typhoon of 1180, the famine of 1181–82, the earthquake
        of 1185. The opening passage frames these disasters: <em>everything
        passes; nothing endures.</em>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The river metaphor in world literature</h2>
      <p>
        The image of the river that flows on but is never the same is a
        cross-cultural intuition: Heraclitus said something similar in the
        6th century BCE ("you cannot step twice into the same river"),
        though it is unlikely Chōmei knew the Greek tradition. The
        Buddhist concept of <em>anicca</em> (impermanence) — central to
        the <em>Heike Monogatari</em> opening as well — is the more
        immediate intellectual source.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The ten-foot square hut</h2>
      <p>
        Chōmei\'s hut, ten feet square (about 3m × 3m), was deliberately the
        smallest dwelling considered habitable. He furnished it sparely: a
        biwa (lute), a koto, a few books, a bowl. The literary essay he wrote
        there became one of the founding texts of the Japanese
        <em>zuihitsu</em> (essay, "following the brush") tradition.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Suggested reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Anthony H. Chambers (trans.), <em>The Ten-Foot Hut</em> (Columbia, 2018).</li>
        <li>Yasuhiko Moriguchi &amp; David Jenkins (trans.), <em>Hōjōki: Visions of a Torn World</em> (Stone Bridge, 1996).</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <hr />

